      "writtenOn": "2017-11-27T18:21:56Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I think it\u0027s a little hard for me to contribute meaningfully to the conversation here because I don\u0027t fully understand the need for swarming\u0027s scheduler to time out immediately if the drain file exists. I\u0027m a little confused though by what you mean by \"swarming\u0027s scheduler\"? The main task loop that launches swarming tasks can\u0027t use mmutex as an entry point to the maintenance mutex (for the reasons listed under \"Swarming\" in https://docs.google.com/document/d/1J5WcsGPDCL1QxS8m9V9qtB6DRtuI7s1wljGFFjHJPug/edit#). As far as I know, there aren\u0027t even any planned clients of the mmutex \"shared\" command.\n\nIt also seems like, conceptually, it would make more sense to separate out the command timeout from the lock acquisition timeout. That would make the swarming command you described the same as mmutex shared --lock_acquisition_timeout\u003d0 --command_timeout\u003d30m -- \u003ccommand\u003e",
      "parentUuid": "b53265d5_c7f424ee",
      "range": {
