      "writtenOn": "2017-11-27T18:21:56Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "+iannucci@chromium.org, who suggested something similar above\n\nAFAICT, the behavior for this wasn\u0027t spelled out explicitly in https://docs.google.com/document/d/1J5WcsGPDCL1QxS8m9V9qtB6DRtuI7s1wljGFFjHJPug/edit#. \n\nI\u0027m not sure how important this check is. It complicates the logic here, though, because we\u0027d have to exit the \"WithSharedBlocking\" block and reenter it once the drain file goes away. I guess we could just put the whole thing in a loop, but it would definitely complicate things a bit.\n\nThe reason I don\u0027t feel it\u0027s important is that, generally, if the drain file doesn\u0027t exist, that means that we\u0027re in one of two states:\n\n1) One other command is running while holding the exclusive lock\n2) Zero or more other commands are running while holding a shared lock\n\nIn the case of 1), we\u0027ll block due to the \"WithSharedBlocking\" command anyhow and get to run after that exclusive command terminates and we can acquire the shared lock.\n\nIn the case of 2), we\u0027ll get to run immediately. \n\nThe one case where this kind of seems to matter is when an exclusive command is queued in between the time that this shared command tried to acquire the lock and the time that the lock was acquired. In this case, I can\u0027t think of any reason that we should give preference to the exclusive command to run over the shared one: the shared one has the lock, and should therefore be given the opportunity to run. It\u0027s not like doing so will cause the exclusive lock seeker to starve: the next shared task to try to run will see that the drain file exists and hold off on performing the command until that drain file goes away and it can acquire the mutex, which seems fair.",
      "parentUuid": "54744da9_d2f8d455",
